blueprint.description:
1. Place the control structure bordering suitably shaped lake.
2. Place reactor modules above it.
3. Place power converter on the right side. Then flip it, and place it on the left side.
4. Place an end cap at the top of the reactors.
5. Hook up fuel, waste, and main power connections.
6. Turn power bridge switch on. Low Fuel and Low Power alarms will sound, supply fuel and warm up reactors and they will stop.
7. Activate lowermost combinator to engage.
8. Once warmed up, turn bridge switch off.
blueprint.label: How To Build The Last Reactor

blueprint.description:
1. Blueprint out additional power conversion modules. The first pass will place landfill.
2. Repeat to place buildings on top of landfill.
3. Leaving the endcap in place, Repeat this process with reactor modules. Build again on top of landfill, like last time.
4. Place a new endcap at the end of the expansion.
5. Delete existing endcap and connect new reactors to old.
6. Ensure everything builds quickly. Leaving fuel loop disconnected can stall reactors.
blueprint.label: Expanding The Last Reactor

blueprint.description:
1. Blueprints which are only half of a structure, are the right side. Flip them to get the left side.
2. They are meant to be placed over water, and they include landfill.
3. They depend on the presence of water which remains exposed in some places.
4. HAZARD CONCRETE is used to denote these locations.
5. Detailed water needs will be in the description.
6. Left/right/up/down are relative to the INITIAL position of the blueprint. keep this in mind if you rotate/flip them.
blueprint.label: About "Structure" Blueprints

blueprint.description:
1. These are optional enhancements to the structures.
2. They are separate because they are tiles (plus walls for alignment), and you can't include landfill and also other tiles on top of it in one blueprint.
3. Place structure blueprints FIRST.
4. They are cosmetic/convenience (the main benefit they provide is the increased movement speed of concrete).
5. Hazard concrete isn't special here like it is in structure blueprints, it's purely cosmetic.
blueprint.label: About "Foundation" Blueprints

blueprint.description: Water requirements: water pump location (1) for uninterruptible control grid power supply. Do not expect to be able to use open space above the blueprint to hook it up, as that space is occupied by heat exchangers. You can move it right or downwards from its current location though, or flip the blueprint to move it to the left side (it will hook up either way, just remember that the controls will be backwards if you do this)
blueprint.label: Controller Module (Structure)

blueprint.description:
No water requirements.

Use enough reactors to completely fill the space between the power conversion modules you build, rounded up.

Landfill on bottom slots into either controller module, or other reactors.

A single yellow belt can support up to 1500 reactors (I haven't tested this, but 1 fuel * 200 seconds * 15 items/s * half belt = 1500). Upgrade the belts if you need more than that.
blueprint.label: Reactor Module (Structure)

blueprint.description: No special water requirements. What did you expect?
blueprint.label: Reactor Endcap (Structure)

blueprint.description:
Water requirements: 16 hookups for heat exchanger bank water supply. Each of the 8 banks has one reactor-side and turbine-side. At least one per bank must be connected (banks require 1134 water/s max), 8 total.

Empty spaces in the blueprint are (possibly) additional sources of water, if a primary location is unavailable.

Water hookups are flip-symmetrical.

Leftmost heat pipes snap ONTO edge of reactor modules.

Power poles and steam buffer snaps ONTO controller module.
blueprint.label: Power Converter (Structure)

blueprint.description: Some nice concrete for the controller area.
blueprint.label: Controller Module (Foundation)

blueprint.description: Drive-thru nuclear reactor. What a world we live in.
blueprint.label: Power Converter (Foundation)

blueprint.description:
Fuels when steam buffer is low or emptying fast.

1. Hook green wire to steam buffer, and red wire to fuel/waste inserters.
2. Set waste inserters to read hand contents in pulse mode, always enabled.
3. Set fuel inserters to read hand contents in pulse mode, enabled when [check] equals [green].
4. Set up desired steam buffer and number of connected tanks, defaults to 4x12500 (inner combinator).
5. Turn inner combinator on to begin fueling, turn off to stop fueling.
blueprint.label: Quick and Dirty Reactor Limiter
